            <div n="1">
                <head>
                    <hi rendition="#i">The Shirt Tree.</hi>
                </head>
                <p>&#x2014;Nature has produced<lb break="yes"/>for man&#x2019;s use and comfort, his actual neces-<lb break="no"/>sities, the bread fruit tree,&#x2014;the cow, or milk<lb break="yes"/>tree,&#x2014;the butter tree,&#x2014;the cabbage tree,&#x2014;<lb break="yes"/>but the beneficence of nature is in South<lb break="yes"/>America taxed for the luxuries of dress.</p>
                <lb break="yes"/>
                <p>&#x201C;We saw (says M. Humboldt) on the<lb break="yes"/>slope of the Cerra
                    Duida, <hi rendition="#i">shirt trees</hi> fifty feet<lb break="yes"/>high. The
                    Indians cut off cylindrical pieces<lb break="yes"/>two feet in diameter, from
                    which they peel<lb break="yes"/>the red and fibrous bark, without making<lb
                        break="yes"/>any longitudinal incision. This bark affords<lb break="yes"
                    />them a sort of garment, which resembles<lb break="yes"/>sacks of a very coarse
                    texture, and without<lb break="yes"/>a seam. The upper opening serves for the<lb
                        break="yes"/>head: and two lateral holes are cut to ad-<lb break="no"/>mit
                    the arms. The natives wear these<lb break="yes"/>shirts of marima in the rainy
                    season: they<lb break="yes"/>have the form of the <hi rendition="#i"
                        >ponchos</hi> and <hi rendition="#i">ruanas</hi> of<lb break="yes"/>cotton,
                    which are so common in New Gre-<lb break="no"/>nada, at Quito, and in Peru. As
                    in these<lb break="yes"/>climates the riches and beneficence of<lb break="yes"
                    />nature are regarded as the primary causes<lb break="yes"/>of the indolence of
                    the inhabitants, the mis-<lb break="no"/>sionaries do not fail to say in showing
                        the<lb break="yes"/>shirts of <hi rendition="#i">marima.</hi> &#x2018;In the
                    forests of the<lb break="yes"/>Oroonoko, garments are found ready made<lb
                        break="yes"/>on the trees.&#x2019; We may add to this tale of<lb break="yes"
                    />the shirts, the pointed caps, which the<lb break="yes"/>spathes of certain
                    palm trees furnish, and<lb break="yes"/>which resemble coarse net-work.</p>
            </div>
